                               Last month, the country stood on shaky ground. Two earthquakes - in quick succession shook the northern belt of India. We realized that our lives hang on a very fragile thread and all that it takes to snap, is a mild tremor. <br />
                                <br />
                                Such calamities make us think of all those foolish times when we put away planning for a rainy day. If only…. if only….
                                The loss of lives, of dear ones, of good health is irreplaceable.  But life must go on.. We will have to rebuild our lives from whatever is left.<br />
                                <br />
                                Thinking of it, this ‘whatever is left’, can be controlled. Can we, should we do something about what we will be left with, in case of a catastrophe? <br />
                                <br />
                                Absolutely, we can and we should – plan for emergencies. <br />
                                <br />
                                <strong>Keep cash at home </strong>- It might be a great idea to have some cash stashed away at home, under the pillow. When disaster strikes you may not be able to run to the bank, or the bank ATM might itself be among the rubbles. Don’t keep a lot of cash at home, we know the dangers. But cash enough to buy food and other basic stuff for about 1 week should be enough.<br />
                                <br />
                               <strong> Build your emergency fund</strong> – Apart from keeping some cash at home, a comfortable 3 – 6 month expenses kept in the savings bank account or liquid funds will help in case of any kind of emergency, like illness or job losses also. This can be built over a period of time but on priority. A better option could also be to take overdrafts approved and made available against assets like fixed deposits, mutual funds or even gold kept in lockers. Your financial planner might be able to guide you on what is the right option for you.<br />
                                <br />
                                <strong>Buy your insurances </strong>– Enough has been said about losing lives and of families left in the lurch after such disasters. So, quite obviously a term plan for the bread winners of the family is in order. You know what can be worse than losing life? Lying critically injured with earnings lost and expenses up there. I guess a health, hospitalization and accident insurance is also absolutely essential. Check with your financial planner for details on which plans, products to buy.<br />
                                <br />
                                <strong>Rebuilding assets </strong>– Okay, the house is now dust, but how will it be if your insurer can foot part of the bill of rebuilding that house? A comprehensive insurance for your house and all its contents would be a blessing then. And this can be purchased at some super low costs. You should get this done.<br />
                                <br />
                                <strong>Safe keep important documents </strong>– Bank details, insurance details, investment details, documents relating to immovable property, will and legal documents are as important as the asset itself. Losing them is like, not being able to eat food that is laid out on the table. It would be a great idea to take 3 copies of all your important financial documents and leave one at home, one in the bank locker and one more with a person you can trust. You will have to experience it to believe how much relief this would be.<br />
                                <br />
                                Consider appointing a power of attorney, who can be in charge of making certain decisions, especially in case of death or disability. <br />
                                <br />
                                <strong>Look into the future with hope </strong>– You can’t wake up every day dreading a mishap might happen. Or can you stop planning for the future whining what the point in all this is, if just a wee bit of shift in the earth’s axis can shatter it all away. Eternal pessimism is a mental sickness. Nothing might happen, your children will grow up in front of your eyes and then you will have to pay for their education and get them married away. Your spouse and you might grow old together and live long. You should have enough money to see you through old age. So, get your planning done and continue investing as if everything is going to be fine.
                                <br/>
                                <br/>
                                It’s a simple choice, in the end. You crib or you plan. 
